# Human Cost Tracker — U.S.–Iran War

A self-updating casualty tracker published via GitHub Pages. Numbers live in JSON files; a GitHub Actions workflow checks sources daily and keeps the page current without touching the HTML.

---

## Repository layout

```
.
├── .github/
│   └── workflows/
│       └── update-data.yml      # daily cron + manual trigger
├── data/
│   ├── casualties.json          # all numbers (source of truth)
│   └── sources.json             # source metadata
├── docs/
│   ├── index.html               # the tracker page
│   ├── data/                    # ← auto-copied here by the update script
│   │   ├── casualties.json
│   │   └── sources.json
│   └── assets/
│       └── js/
│           └── data-loader.js   # fetches JSON, populates data-* elements
├── scripts/
│   └── fetch-and-update.js      # Node update script
└── package.json
```

---

## GitHub Pages setup

1. Push this repo to GitHub.
2. Go to **Settings → Pages**.
3. Under **Source**, choose **Deploy from a branch**.
4. Set branch to `main` and folder to `/docs`.
5. Click **Save**.

Your tracker will be live at `https://<you>.github.io/<repo>/` within a minute or two.

> **Why `/docs`?** GitHub Pages serves everything inside `docs/` as the web root. The update script copies `data/*.json` into `docs/data/` automatically, so the page can fetch them over HTTP.

---

## How the data-attribute system works

The HTML uses three custom attributes. The loader (`docs/assets/js/data-loader.js`) fetches `docs/data/casualties.json` and `docs/data/sources.json` on page load and populates every matching element.

### `data-metric="<key>"`

Replaces the element's text content with `metrics[key].display` from `casualties.json`.

```html
<div class="metric-number" data-metric="iran.reportedDeaths">&gt;1,900</div>
```

Keys follow the pattern `<region>.<stat>`, e.g. `iran.reportedDeaths`, `us.militaryWounded`.

### `data-metric-source="<key>"`

Populates with `"<source> · <date>"` from the same metrics entry.

```html
<div class="metric-source" data-metric-source="iran.reportedDeaths">IFRC via Reuters · Apr 2</div>
```

### `data-bar="<key>"`

Updates the animated bar's `--fill-width` CSS variable, inner span text, and `.bar-meta` copy.

```html
<div class="bar-fill" style="--fill-width: 76%;" data-bar="iran.reportedDeaths"><span>&gt;1,900</span></div>
```

### `data-tree="<key>"`

Updates `.tree-label`, `.tree-number`, and `.tree-desc` inside the tree card.

```html
<div class="tree-card level-0" data-tree="iran.total">
  <div class="tree-label">…</div>
  <div class="tree-number">&gt;1,900</div>
  <div class="tree-desc">…</div>
</div>
```

### `data-source-id="<id>"`

Matches against `sources.json` and updates role, title, date, description, and link href.

```html
<div class="source-card" data-source-id="reuters-roundup">…</div>
```

> **Graceful fallback:** If the JSON fetch fails (e.g. opening the HTML as a local file), the loader logs a warning and the page displays the static values already baked into the HTML.

---

## Updating numbers

### Option A — Manual update via GitHub Actions UI

1. Go to **Actions → Update casualty data → Run workflow**.
2. In the `set_flags` input, enter space-separated key=value pairs:

   ```
   metrics.iran.reportedDeaths.raw=2100 metrics.iran.reportedDeaths.display=>2,100
   ```

3. Click **Run workflow**. The action updates `casualties.json`, validates it, commits, and pushes.

### Option B — Local update

```bash
# Install (no external deps — uses Node built-ins only)
npm install

# Set one or more values
node scripts/fetch-and-update.js \
  --set metrics.iran.reportedDeaths.raw=2100 \
  --set metrics.iran.reportedDeaths.display=">2,100"

# Validate without writing
node scripts/fetch-and-update.js --validate

# Check that source URLs are reachable
node scripts/fetch-and-update.js --check-only
```

Then commit and push. GitHub Pages will redeploy automatically.

### Option C — Edit JSON directly

Edit `data/casualties.json`, run `node scripts/fetch-and-update.js --validate` to confirm consistency, then commit and push. The workflow will sync `docs/data/` on the next run.

---

## Automated daily check

`.github/workflows/update-data.yml` runs every day at 08:00 UTC. It:

1. Pings each source URL with a HEAD request to check reachability.
2. Stamps `lastUpdated` and `conflictDays` in `casualties.json`.
3. Copies JSON into `docs/data/`.
4. Commits and pushes if anything changed.

The workflow **does not automatically scrape new numbers** — that would require source-specific parsers that break whenever the sites change. Instead it keeps the data file fresh and flags which sources to check manually.

---

## `casualties.json` schema

```jsonc
{
  "lastUpdated": "YYYY-MM-DD",        // set automatically by the update script
  "conflictStart": "YYYY-MM-DD",      // set once, used to compute conflictDays
  "conflictDays": 39,                 // computed automatically

  "metrics": {
    "<region>.<stat>": {
      "display": ">1,900",            // human-readable string shown on page
      "raw": 1900,                    // integer for logic checks
      "source": "IFRC via Reuters",   // source name shown in metric-source
      "date": "Apr 2"                 // date shown in metric-source
    }
  },

  "bars": {
    "<region>.<stat>": {
      "fillPct": 76,                  // percentage width (0–100)
      "display": ">1,900",            // text shown inside / beside bar
      "meta": "Scale: 0 to 2,500…",  // shown in .bar-meta
      "color": "red",                 // "red" or "amber"
      "scaleMax": 2500                // reference only (for recalculating fillPct)
    }
  },

  "tree": {
    "<region>.<stat>": {
      "display": ">1,900",
      "raw": 1900,
      "label": "Iran: all reported deaths",
      "desc": "…"
    }
  }
}
```

---

## Adding a new region or metric

1. Add an entry to `data/casualties.json` under `metrics` (and `bars` / `tree` if needed).
2. Add a corresponding `data-metric="<key>"` attribute to the HTML element.
3. Run `node scripts/fetch-and-update.js --validate` to check consistency.
4. Commit and push.

